President Barack Obama has issued a proclamation declaring December 10, 2011, as Human Rights Day and the week beginning December 10, 2011, as Human Rights Week. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights adopted by the United Nations General Assembly on December 10, 1948. It highlights the fundamental freedoms of all individuals, regardless of gender, race, religion, nationality, sexual orientation, or disability, and calls for the elimination of extrajudicial killing, torture, oppression, and discrimination. The proclamation also acknowledges the progress made in consolidating democracy and expanding freedoms worldwide, particularly in the Middle East and North Africa. President Obama calls upon the people of the United States to observe these occasions with appropriate ceremonies and activities.